                     Metal nanoparticles are one of the types of noncarbon-based materials, the dimensions (length, width or thickness) of which range between 1 and 100nm. They have superior properties, such as:

                           •

plasmon excitation;


                           •

large surface-to-volume ratio;


                           •

quantum confinement;


                           •

large surface energies;


                           •

short range ordering;


                           •

a large number of low-coordination sites.

In another study, Vahedi et al. suggested a carbon paste electrode modified with ionic liquid-MgO nanoparticles (MgO/NPs/IL/CPE) for the determination of methyldopa in pharmaceutical and patient human urine samples. At pH 7.0, the designed nanosensor has a linear correlation with the concentration of methyldopa in the range of 0.08–380μmolL−1 with a detection limit of 0.03μmolL−1 (Vahedi et al., 2013) (Fig. 5
                     ). Other studies related to metallic nanomaterials-based nanosensors are summarized in Table 2
                     .

In their work, Hu et al. developed a chemical nanosensor based on molecularly imprinted polymers doped with silver nanoparticles (AgNPs@MISPE) for the rapid detection of caffeine in wastewater using the surface-enhanced Raman scattering technique. The nanocomposite was first characterized by Fourier transform infrared spectroscopy (FTIR), X-ray diffraction (XRD), and ultraviolet-visible (UV-vis) spectroscopy. The AgNPs@MISPE was used to detect caffeine with a relative standard deviation value of 4.8% and with good repeatability at a relative standard deviation value of 8.7%. Moreover, the detection limit was 100ngL−1 (Fig. 6
                     ). Other studies related to polymer-based chemical nanosensors are summarized in Table 3
                     .
